[recv] {"type": "turn_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Evaluating Java and Groovy paths**\n\nI'm exploring whether to use native or Java, considering a potential issue where Groovy init errors may not be properly handled in the JVM. It seems like catching should not swallow errors during JVM execution. I'm also looking at executing a closure via a public API without content-type, but there are some complexities with class references and instrumentation. Perhaps reflection isn't allowed directly, and I'm not sure if MethodHandles will be instrumented appropriately either. It could be a package-private issue.\n\n**Inspecting class loading and access**\n\nI see that the closure class is loaded from a dependency jar and the package isn't sealed, which is good. I’m wondering if lookup.findStatic can resolve methods in the test class loader. It seems like our helper might not have been included because the tests are outside the library packages. All files might be untracked, which is problematic. To refine this, I should test a public API that causes closure class initialization with the default parser, possibly using a Groovy MOP property for accessing class$.\n\n**Investigating Java class usage**\n\nI'm examining the source compiled with the target Java to see how the class$ helper is being generated but unused outside possibly in a call site array. Javap doesn’t show it as being used elsewhere, which might suggest it's only for coverage instrumentation. The dynamic-access report indicates that the call site must invoke class$ for proper coverage. I’m considering that Class#forName's stack frame might expect \"class$\" as a method name and that it records the caller class. I wonder if this class$ isn't instrumented in the transformed jar.", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_092b152a47ada7d6016a01ae2bf590819e9898a391b5a784ec\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"encrypted_content\":\"gAAAAABqAa5E2-YCqQENoALd7ILbzncEa6e8Oe2ebSh0